Overview

Russia is located in eastern Europe and northern Asia and was the former main republic of the USSR until it became independent in 1991. It is the world's largest country and spans 11 timezones. The country contains Europe's largest river (Volga) and lake (Ladoga) along with the world's deepest lake (Baikal). Russia has an extreme cold climate and records the world's coldest temperatures outside of the north/south poles. The Russian population is mostly made up of ethnic Russians and are concentrated in the European portion of the country. The capital, Moscow, and the city of St. Petersburg are the two largest cultural and financial hubs of Russia. The Russian republic was established following the 1917 Russian Revolution and became part of the USSR in 1922. From the end of WWII until the fall of the USSR in 1991, Russia played a major role in the Cold War with the US. In 1991, Russia joined the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), a loose coalition of former Soviet republics. Following the fall of communism, Russia has endured a generally weak economy, high inflation, and a myriad of social ills but nonetheless has remained a major world super power. Throughout all of Russia's history, they have boasted excellence in both the arts and sciences. [1]

Land

Borders

  • Neighboring Countries: North Korea, China, Mongolia, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan, Georgia in the south. Ukraine, Belarus, Latvia, Estonia, Lithuania, Poland, Finland, and Norway in the west. [1]
  • Water: Arctic ocean in north, Pacific ocean in east. Baltic sea, Black sea, Sea of Azov, and Caspian Sea. [1]

Relief

Kola-Karelian Region [1] [2] [3]

Map
Elevation
  • Karelia (Карелия): max elevation is 1,896 ft., average elevation is below 650 feet
  • Kola Peninsula (Кольский полуостров): max elevation is nearly 3,907 ft.
Notes
  • Karelia (Карелия): Low ridges and knolls alternate with lake and marsh filled hollows. Is located in the Karelia republic. Majority of the surface of the land is broad, flat, swampy plains.
  • Kola Peninsula (Кольский полуостров): Highest points are in the Khibiny mountain range and the Lovozorskye Tundry range. Is located in the Murmansk oblast. Land in south falls to a low swampy coast. Has world's largest deposits of apatite (used for fertilizer production).

Russian Plain [1]

Map
Elevation
  • Max elevation: 1,896 feet, average elevation: below 650 feet
Notes
  • Smallest Russian relief region
  • Low ridges and knolls alternate with lake and marsh filled hollows

Ural Mountains [1] [2] [3]

Map
Elevation
  • Max elevation: 6,217 ft (Mount Narodnaya), average elevation between 3000-5000 ft.
  • Polar Urals: max elevation is Mount Rayer at 4829 ft, average elevation is 3500 ft.
  • Nether-Polar Urals: max elevation is Mount Narodnaya at 6217 ft, Mount Karpinsk is also 6161 ft.
  • Northern Urals: max elevation is Mount Telpos-Iz at 5305 ft, average elevation is 3300 ft.
  • Central Urals: max elevation is Mount Sredny Baseg at 3261 ft, average elevation is 1600 ft.
  • Southern Urals: max elevation is Mount Yamantau at 5380 ft, average elevation is 2000-3900 ft.
Notes
  • Forms the traditional physiographic boundary between Europe and Asia
  • Drain into Arctic Ocean and Caspian Sea
  • Polar Urals: 240 miles, covered in glaciers and permafrost
  • Nether Polar Urals: 140 miles, covered in glaciers and permafrost
  • Northern Urals: 340 miles, many summits are flat, weathering has resulted in seas of stone in the north
  • Central Urals: 200 miles, most summits are smooth and isolated
  • Southern Urals: 340 miles

West Siberian Plain [1] [2]

Map
Elevation
  • Max elevation: max elevation is 650 ft, average elevation is 330 ft.
Notes
  • One of the world's largest flatlands, area of nearly 1,200,000 square miles
  • Drained by Ob, Irtysh, and Yenisey rivers
  • Parts are underlain by oil fields and large natural gas deposits
  • Most of the population lives in the higher and drier south

Central Siberian Plateau [1] [2] [3] [4]

Map
Elevation
  • Max elevation: max elevation is Putoran Mountains at 5581 ft, average elevation is 1650-2300 ft.
  • North Siberian Lowland: 165-230 ft above sea level.
Notes
  • Area of 600,000 square miles
  • Tundra in the north, steppe-grasslands in the south
  • Makes up Krasnoyarsk Kray, Sakha, and Irkutsk
  • North Siberian Lowland: extremely swampy, has tundra vegetation
  • Putoran Mountains: located in Krasnoyarsk Kray, climate is mountain tundra
